By Oluwamayomikun Orekoya  Egyptian referee Mohamed Maarouf Eid Mansour will be in the centre when the Olympic Eagles take on Cote d’Ivoire in their opening game of the Total U-23 Africa Cup of Nations at the Al Salam Stadium, Cairo tomorrow. Maroof has been a FIFA-badge referee since 2014 and was in charge of Lobi Star’s 2-1 win over Mamelodi Sundowns of South Africa in the Champions League in Enugu in January. The Egyptian centre referee will be assisted by his fellow countryman Youssef Wahid Youssef Elbosaty and Firmino Bassafim from Guinea-Bissau, while the fourth official is Souleiman Ahmed Djama from Djibouti. Meanwhile, CAF has named CD Huesca’s Kelechi Nwakali among the top eight players to watch in the competition. Nwakali, formerly with Arsenal, was Nigeria’s captain in the 2015 U-17 FIFA World Cup in Chile where he guided them to their record fifth title, winning the Golden Ball in the process. He has also featured for MVV Massstricht, VVV Venlo (Both in Holland) and Porto B in Portugal. Other players listed are Ramadan Sobhy (Egypt), Aly Mallé (Mali), Eric Ayuk (Cameroon), Owusu Kwabena (Ghana), Christian Kouamé (Cote d’Ivoire), Luther Singh (South Africa) and Patson Daka (Zambia).  